06013nam a22009975i 9780674418356DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20132000mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)935283550  a97806744183567 a10.4159/harvard.97806744183562doi  a(DE-B1597)252720  a(OCoLC)900798574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDD228.5 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a943.08/41 aRepp, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReformers, Critics, and the Paths of German Modernity :bAnti-Politics and the Search for Alternatives, 1890-1914 /cKevin Repp.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (358 p.) :b8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. Coming to Terms with the Future -- tCHAPTER 1.The Generation of 1890 -- tCHAPTER 2. Adolf Damaschke and the Language of Popular Nationalism -- tCHAPTER 3. Gertrud Bäumer’s New Liberalism and the Politics of Womanhood -- tCHAPTER 4. Werner Sombart’s “Anti-Politik” and the Vicissitudes of Socialism “as a Cultural Factor” -- tCHAPTER 5. The Wilhelmine Reform Milieu -- tEPILOGUE. War and Revolutions -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Modernity" was an inescapable fact of life for the first generation to come of age in the German Empire. Even the most extreme political opponents saw the chaotic transformation of all spheres of life in the wake of industrial capitalism as the central problem facing young men and women at the fin de siècle. This fresh look at Wilhelmine perceptions of modernity challenges both the traditional emphasis on anti-modernism as a peculiarly German response that led to the rise of National Socialism, and the more recent post-Foucauldian studies on the "pathologies of modernity," which point instead to an unreflective faith in science and efficiency on the part of German progressives. Shifting the focus away from radical extremes on either side, Kevin Repp explores the more moderate agendas of hundreds of mainstream intellectuals and activists from diverse social backgrounds who sought to surmount the human costs of industrialization without relinquishing its positive potential. Repp combines detailed case studies of Adolf Damaschke, Gertrud Bäumer, and Werner Sombart with an innovative prosopography of their milieu to show how leading reformers enlisted familiar tropes of popular nationalism, eugenics, and cultural pessimism in formulating pragmatic solutions that would be at once modern and humane. Easily obscured by radical voices on right and left, this quiet search for alternatives nevertheless succeeded in building a nationwide network of educational centers, associative ties, and institutions that substantially altered the landscape of Wilhelmine political culture in the decades before the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBodenreform. 0aFrauenbewegung. 0aGeschichte Deutschlands. 0aIntellectual life. 0aModernisme (cultuur). 0aPolitical culturezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical culture. 0aPolitical science. 0aPolitieke cultuur. 0aPolitische Kultur. 0aSocial policy. 0aSocial reformerszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial reformers. 0aSociale hervormingen. 0aSozialismus. 0aSozialreform. 4aGermany -- Politics and government -- 19th century. 4aGermany -- Social policy -- 19th century. 4aHISTORY / General. 4aPolitical culture -- Germany -- History -- 19th century. 4aSocial reformers -- Germany -- History -- 19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Com